 Scotland at an early date and is the name of an important and powerful Scottish family.","Irish: adopted as an equivalent ofvarious Gaelic names (see   Lindsey  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Linzy","meanings":["Altered form of Scottish, Irish, or English   Lindsay   or   Lindsey  . Compare   Lenzy  ."]},{"name":"Linzey","meanings":["English: variant of   Lindsay   or   Lindsey  ."]},{"name":"Lindsey","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Lindsay  .","Irish: shortened and Anglicized form of various Gaelic surnames, as for example <b>Ó Loingsigh</b> (see   Lynch   1), <b>Mac Giolla Fhionntóg</b> (see   McClintock  ), and <b>Ó Fhloinn</b> (see   Flynn   and   Lynn  )."]},{"name":"Lincoln","meanings":["English: habitational name from the city of Lincoln, so named from an original British name <i>Lindo-</i> ‘lake’ + Latin <i>colonia</i> ‘settlement, colony’. The place was an important administrative center during the Roman occupation of Britain and in the Middle Ages it was a center for the manufacture of cloth, including the famous ‘Lincoln green’.","African American: adoption of the surname in 1 above, in honor of Abraham Lincoln, the 16th president of the US, who abolished slavery.","History: Abraham Lincoln (1809–65), 16th president of the US, was the son of an illiterate laborer, descended from Samuel Lincoln, who had emigrated from England to MA in 1637."]},{"name":"Linsey","meanings":["Scottish, Irish, or English: variant of   Lindsay   or   Lindsey  .","Americanized form of German   Linse   or Swiss German <b>Linsi</b>, see   Lins  ."]}]},{"name":"Crawford","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Transferred use of the surname, originally a local name from any of the various places so named from Old English with <i>crāwe</i> ‘crow’ + <i>ford</i> ‘ford’, for example in Dorset, Lanarkshire, and Lancashire."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Crawford Lindsay was born in 1194, in Scotland, Uni